title.narrative: OUTPUT 3.2 PREVENT AND REDUCE CHILDHOODILLNESSES

description.narrative: Output 2 (Prevent and reduce childhood illnesses): Government and partners at national and subnational levels have strengthened capacity for the prevention, control and elimination of major childhood illnesses, particularly those resulting from vaccine- preventable and communicable diseases, which contributes to Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care (Covid), Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Newborns, children and adolescents in Indonesia's decentralized context live in healthy environments and have equitable access to high quality primary health care, especially in most marginalized, underserved regions.

title.narrative: Output 2 (Prevent and reduce childhood illnesses): Government and partners at national and subnational levels have strengthenedcapacity for the prevention, control and elimination of major childhood illnesses, particularly those resulting from vaccine-preventable and communicable diseases

description.narrative: UNICEF’s work on improving child health outcomes is a critical component of the overall health portfolio. Focusing on vaccine-preventable and communicable diseases, significant efforts were made on several fronts. UNICEF is one of the leading agencies assisting the Government with COVID-19 vaccine deployment while ensuring continuity of routine immunization. UNICEF is supporting scale-up of malaria elimination in high-endemic districts. UNICEF is providing technical expertise for the implementation of integrated child health services, including for pneumonia and diarrhoea. In response to the high burden of childhood tuberculosis (TB), UNICEF started working on this issue while continuing interventions for paediatric COVID-19. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:31/01/2022
